{"title_page": "Joelinton", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Joelinton\n|image = Joelinton.jpg\n|image_size = \n|caption = Joelinton playing for [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]] against [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] in May 2019\n|fullname = Joelinton C\u00e1ssio Apolin\u00e1rio de Lira<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1335777 |title=2019/20 Premier League squads confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=3 September 2019 |accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1996|8|14|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Alian\u00e7a]], Brazil\n|height = 1.86 m\n|position = [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|Centre forward]]\n|currentclub = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n|clubnumber = 9\n|youthyears1 = 2010\u20132014\n|youthclubs1 = [[Sport Club do Recife|Sport Recife]]\n|years1 = 2014\u20132015\n|clubs1 = [[Sport Club do Recife|Sport Recife]] \n|caps1 = 12\n|goals1 = 3\n|years2 = 2015\u20132019\n|clubs2 = [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]]\n|caps2 =  29\n|goals2 = 7\n|years3 = 2016\u20132018     \n|clubs3 = \u2192 [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Wien]] (loan) \n|caps3 = 60 \n|goals3 = 15\n|years4 = 2019\u2013\n|clubs4 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n|caps4 = 29\n|goals4 = 1\n|nationalyears1 = 2012 |nationalteam1 = [[Brazil national under-17 football team|Brazil U17]] |nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 2\n|club-update = 18:38, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n|ntupdate = 7 October 2016\n|medaltemplates =\n}}\n'''Joelinton C\u00e1ssio Apolin\u00e1rio de Lira''' (born 14 August 1996), known as '''Joelinton''', is a Brazilian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre forward]] for English club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]. Starting his career with [[Sport Club do Recife|Sport Recife]], Joelinton joined [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|Hoffenheim]] in 2015, and was loaned to [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Wien]] for two years from 2016. He is often regarded as one of the best players in the world. He has also been capped for the [[Brazil national under-17 football team|Brazil under-17 national team]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Sport Recife===\nBorn in [[Alian\u00e7a]], [[Pernambuco]], Joelinton joined [[Sport Club do Recife|Sport Recife]] in 2012 and spent two years playing in the youth team. He was promoted to the senior squad in 2013, but it was not until March 2014 that he made his professional debut, in a [[2014 Copa do Nordeste|Copa do Nordeste]] match against city rivals [[Santa Cruz Futebol Clube|Santa Cruz]]. He came on as a 62nd-minute substitute for [[Neto Baiano]] in the 2\u20131 away semi-final win (4\u20131 aggregate).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitipaldi |first1=Lucas |title=En meio a pol\u00eamicas, Sport bate o Santa e est\u00e1 na final da Copa do NE|trans-title=Amidst controversies, Sport beat Santa and are in the NE Cup Final |url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/jogo/copa-do-nordeste-2014/19-03-2014/santa-cruz-sport.html |accessdate=19 August 2018 |publisher=Globo |date=19 March 2014 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> Sport won the cup with a 3\u20131 aggregate win over [[Cear\u00e1 Sporting Club|Cear\u00e1]] in the final; Joelinton did not play. He was on the bench six times in the [[Campeonato Pernambucano]] season, which they also won.\n\nIn the [[2014 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A]] season, Joelinton made seven appearances towards the end of the campaign. He scored his first career goal on 23 November in a 2\u20132 home draw with [[Fluminense]], and on the last day he scored the only goal against [[S\u00e3o Paulo FC|S\u00e3o Paulo]] after four minutes.<ref>{{cite news |title=Garoto Joelinton marca, e Sport bate o S\u00e3o Paulo na Arena Pernambuco|trans-title=Lad Joelinton scores, and Sport beat  S\u00e3o Paulo in the Arena Pernambuco|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/brasileirao-serie-a/noticia/2014/12/garoto-joelinton-marca-e-sport-bate-o-sao-paulo-na-arena-pernambuco.html |accessdate=19 August 2018 |publisher=Globo |date=7 December 2014 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\nJoelinton established himself in the first team in the 2015 state league. However, he received two straight red cards in the second phase, against Santa Cruz and [[Clube N\u00e1utico Capibaribe|N\u00e1utico]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Sport atropela o Santa no segundo tempo e larga na frente no estadual |trans-title=Sport trample Santa in the second half and extend their lead in the state championship|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/jogo/pernambucano-2015/31-01-2015/santa-cruz-sport.html |accessdate=19 August 2018 |publisher=Globo |date=31 January 2015 |language=Portuguese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sport vence por 2 a 0 e deixa N\u00e1utico em situa\u00e7\u00e3o complicada no Pernambucano |trans-title=Sport win 2\u20130 and leave N\u00e1utico in a complicated situation in the Pernambucano|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/pe/futebol/campeonato-pernambucano/jogo/22-03-2015/nautico-sport/ |accessdate=19 August 2018 |publisher=Globo |date=22 March 2015 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n\n===Hoffenheim===\nIn June 2015, [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|Hoffenheim]] signed Joelinton on a five-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hoffenheim verpflichtet Brasilianer Joelinton|trans-title=Hoffenheim sign Brazilian Joelinton|work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/news/sport/fussball-hoffenheim-verpflichtet-brasilianer-joelinton-dpa.urn-newsml-dpa-com-20090101-150610-99-09224 |accessdate=18 August 2018 |date=10 June 2015 |language=German}}</ref> He played only once in his first season in Germany, as a last-minute substitute for [[Jonathan Schmid]] in a 1\u20130 loss at [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]] on 18 December.<ref>{{cite news |title=Choupo-Motings Schienbein bringt den S04-Sieg|trans-title=Choupo-Moting's shinbone brings S04 victory |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/spieltag/1-bundesliga/2015-16/17/2855077/spielbericht_fc-schalke-04-2_1899-hoffenheim-3209.html |accessdate=18 August 2018 |work=kicker |date=18 December 2015 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Rapid Wien====\n[[File:FC Red Bull Salzburg gegen SK Rapid Wien (10. September 2017) 12.jpg|thumb|upright|Joelinton (left) and [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Salzburg]]'s [[Igor Julio dos Santos de Paulo|Igor]] in September 2017]]\nOn 23 June 2016, Joelinton was loaned to [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Wien]] for two years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ein Brasilianer st\u00fcrmt f\u00fcr Rapid|trans-title=A Brazilian up front for Rapid|url=https://derstandard.at/2000039671429/Ein-Brasilianer-stuermt-fuer-Rapid |accessdate=18 August 2018 |work=Der Standard |date=23 June 2016 |language=German}}</ref> He made his debut on 8 July in the first round of the [[Austrian Cup]] against [[Austrian Regionalliga East|Regionalliga Ost]] club [[FC Karabakh Wien]], scoring the opening goal of a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=3:1! Rapid best\u00e4tigt Favoritenrolle gegen Karabakh|trans-title=3\u20131! Rapid confirm favourites tag against Karabakh|url=http://sport.oe24.at/fussball/fussball-national/bundesliga/rapid-wien/OeFB-Cup-Rapid-bestaetigt-Favoritenrolle-gegen-Karabakh/242752023 |accessdate=18 August 2018 |publisher=Sport 24 |date=8 July 2016 |language=German}}</ref> In the semi-finals on 26 April 2017, he scored an added-time winner at home to [[LASK Linz]] as ''Die Gr\u00fcn-Wei\u00dfen'' reached the final for the first time in 12 years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Joelinton fires Rapid into final! |url=https://www.skrapid.at/en/home/news/news/latest-news/2017/04/joelinton-fires-rapid-into-final/ |accessdate=18 August 2018 |publisher=SK Rapid Wien |date=26 April 2017}}</ref> He equalised in the final at the [[Worthersee Stadion]] on 1 June, but [[FC Red Bull Salzburg]] won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |title=Red Bulls win historic fourth double! |url=https://www.redbullsalzburg.at/en/fc-red-bull-salzburg/news/saison_2016_17/red-bulls-win-historic-fourth-double-.html |accessdate=18 August 2018 |publisher=FC Red Bull Salzburg |date=1 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nJoelinton played all ten of Rapid's [[2016\u201317 UEFA Europa League]] matches, scoring in a 3\u20132 win over [[K.R.C. Genk|Genk]] on 15 September and a 1\u20131 draw with [[Athletic Bilbao]] at the [[Allianz Stadion]] on 8 December.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hackl |first1=Christian |title=Perfekter EL-Auftakt f\u00fcr Rapid gegen Genk |trans-title=Perfect EL debut for Rapid against Genk|url=https://derstandard.at/2000044457277/Perfekter-Auftakt-fuer-Rapid |accessdate=18 August 2018 |work=Der Standard |date=15 September 2016 |language=German}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rapid verabschiedet sich mit 1:1 gegen Bilbao|trans-title=Rapid leave with 1\u20131 against Bilbao |url=https://derstandard.at/2000049005635/Ausgeschieden-Austria-kassiert-drei-Tore-in-Ueberzahl |accessdate=18 August 2018 |work=Der Standard |date=8 December 2016 |language=German}}</ref> On the domestic front in the [[Austrian Football Bundesliga]], he recorded 8 goals in 33 games \u2013 including one to cap a 4\u20131 victory at [[Wiener Derby|city rivals]] [[FK Austria Wien]] on 7 August<ref>{{cite news |title=Rapid gewinnt 318. Wiener Derby |trans-title=Rapid win 318th Viennese Derby|url=https://www.kleinezeitung.at/sport/fussball/oesterreich/bundesliga/5064788/Auswaertssieg_Rapid-gewinnt-318-Wiener-Derby |accessdate=18 August 2018 |work=Kleine Zeitung |date=7 August 2016 |language=German}}</ref> \u2013 but the Viennese club finished 5th of 10 teams and missed out on European football.\n\nOn 22 July 2017, the first game of the [[2017\u201318 Austrian Football Bundesliga|new season]], Joelinton was sent off after 23 minutes in a 2\u20132 home draw with [[SV Mattersburg]], for kicking back after being fouled by [[Michael Novak (footballer)|Michael Novak]].<ref>{{cite news |title=2:2! Rapid verschenkt Auftaktsieg gegen Mattersburg! |trans-title=2\u20132! Rapid miss out on opening win against Mattersburg!|url=http://www.ligaportal.at/bundesliga/spielberichte/2617-2-2-rapid-verschenkt-auftaktsieg-gegen-mattersburg |accessdate=18 August 2018 |publisher=Liga Portal |date=22 July 2017 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n====Return====\nOn his return to Hoffenheim, Joelinton was given a first start in a [[DFB-Pokal]] first round match at [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]], and scored a [[hat-trick]] in a 6\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-centroavante do Sport faz 'hat-trick' na Copa da Alemanha|trans-title=Ex-Sport centre forward scores 'hat-trick' in German Cup |url=https://jconline.ne10.uol.com.br/canal/esportes/futebol/noticia/2018/08/18/ex-centroavante-do-sport-faz-hat-trick-na-copa-da-alemanha-351436.php |accessdate=18 August 2018 |publisher=UOL |date=18 August 2018 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> He netted his first [[Bundesliga]] goal on 22 September to open a 1\u20131 home draw with [[Borussia Dortmund]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Hoffenheim 1\u20131 Borussia Dortmund |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45603127 |accessdate=23 October 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2018}}</ref> and as a substitute on 23 October he scored an added-time equaliser for a 3\u20133 draw against [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] in a Champions League group game at the [[Rhein-Neckar-Arena]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Joelinton strikes late to give Hoffenheim share of the spoils against Lyon |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/hoffenheim-lyon-live-champions-league-line-ups-stats-memphis-fekir-reiss-nelson-515511.jsp |accessdate=23 October 2018 |publisher=Bundesliga |date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\nOn 23 July 2019, Joelinton joined [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on a six-year deal for a reported club record fee of \u00a340 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Magpies confirm club record signing |url=https://www.nufc.co.uk/news/latest-news/magpies-confirm-club-record-signing/ |accessdate=23 July 2019 |publisher=Newcastle United|date=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49039959|title=Joelinton: Newcastle sign Brazilian striker from Hoffenheim|date=2019-07-23|access-date=2020-01-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> He made his debut on 11 August, starting in their 1\u20130 home loss to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]; he and teammate [[Miguel Almir\u00f3n]] were criticised by the club's all-time record scorer [[Alan Shearer]] for their performances.<ref>{{cite news |title=Newcastle United round-up: Alan Shearer criticises duo, Steve Bruce possible reunion plus young midfielder turned down Barcelona move |url=https://www.shieldsgazette.com/sport/football/newcastle-united/newcastle-united-round-up-alan-shearer-criticises-duo-steve-bruce-possible-reunion-plus-young-midfielder-turned-down-barcelona-move-489793 |accessdate=19 August 2019 |work=The Shields Gazette |date=12 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nJoelinton scored his first Premier League goal on 25 August in a 1\u20130 victory away at [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/aug/25/tottenham-newcastle-premier-league-match-report|title=Joelinton secures Newcastle\u2019s first points in surprise win at Tottenham|website=The Guardian|date=25 August 2019|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> It took him until 14 January 2020 to score his second goal for the club, netting the final goal in a 4\u20131 [[2019\u201320_FA_Cup#Third_Round_Proper|FA Cup]] Third Round replay victory over [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/18160286.newcastle-united-4-rochdale-1/|title=Newcastle United 4 Rochdale 1|website=The Northern Echo|date=14 January 2020|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nJoelinton was capped four times by the [[Brazil national under-17 football team|Brazil under-17 national team]] in 2012, scoring two goals.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Updated|4 February 2020}}<ref>